<h1> German Grammar: A Beginner's Guide</h1>
<p>
    German grammar is a complex and challenging subject. This guide is designed to help beginners understand the basics of German grammar.
</p>
<p>
    <h2> Nouns</h2>
    Nouns are the names of people, places, and things. In German, all nouns are capitalized.
</p>
<p>
    <h2> Articles</h2>
    Articles are words that are used to indicate the gender and number of a noun. In German, there are three articles: der, die, and das.
</p>
<p>
    <h2> Verbs</h2>
    Verbs are words that are used to indicate actions or states of being. In German, verbs are conjugated to indicate the subject of the sentence.
</p>
<p>
    <h2> Adjectives</h2>
    Adjectives are words that are used to describe nouns. In German, adjectives are declined to match the gender, number, and case of the noun they modify.
</p>
<p>
    <h2> Pronouns</h2>
    Pronouns are words that are used to replace nouns. In German, pronouns are declined to match the gender, number, and case of the noun they replace.
</p>
